Asclepias syriaca is a species of plant commonly known as common milkweed or butterfly flower.
It is a tall plant that can grow up to 6 feet in height with a broad leaf shape.
The leaves are green and have a rough, hairy texture.
The flowers are small and pinkish-purple in color with a unique star shape.
The plant contains a milky sap that is toxic to many animals but attracts monarch butterflies.
Asclepias syriaca is native to North America and can be found in meadows, fields, and along roadsides.
It is commonly used in gardens as a natural and attractive way to control pests and support butterfly populations.
